## Implementation Plan: `mistral-instruct-v3` Chat Template Handler

**All changes go in `common/chat.cpp` only** — no header or existing handler modifications.

### 4 additions to `common/chat.cpp`:

1. **`MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3_TEMPLATE_SRC` constant** (~line 568, after `CHATML_TEMPLATE_SRC`)  
   A `#define` with the canonical Mistral Instruct v0.3 Jinja template: extracts an optional leading system message, prepends it to the first user turn only, wraps every user turn in `[INST] … [/INST]`, and terminates assistant turns with `</s>`.

2. **Named-registration block** (~line 613, before the existing `chatml` check in `common_chat_templates_init()`)  
   ```cpp
   if (default_template_src == "mistral-instruct-v3") {
       default_template_src = MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3_TEMPLATE_SRC;
   }
   ```
   Allows explicit `--chat-template mistral-instruct-v3` selection without touching the enum or header.

3. **Handler function** (~line 824, before `common_chat_params_init_ministral_3()`)  
   ```cpp
   static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
       const common_chat_template & tmpl,
       const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {
       common_chat_params data;
       data.prompt = common_chat_template_direct_apply(tmpl, inputs);
       data.format = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_CONTENT_ONLY;
       return data;
   }
   ```

4. **Auto-detection block** (~line 1689, before `return std::nullopt;` in `common_chat_try_specialized_template()`)  
   ```cpp
   if (src.find("[INST]") != std::string::npos &&
       src.find("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") == std::string::npos &&
       src.find("[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]") == std::string::npos) {
       LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: mistral-instruct-v3\n");
       return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);
   }
   ```
   The double-absence check (`[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` absent, `[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]` absent) is exactly what distinguishes this from Ministral 3 and from Mistral v3/v3-tekken respectively.

